content.description: An offwidth crack - some people love this thing and others treat it like the plague.  Sit start with a toe jammed in the crack beneath the overhang and find a way to get off the ground.  If you reach back far enough there are hidden jugs, although it can be climbed either way.  Struggle upwards until you can layback on larger holds and topout.  If you're smart, you'll tape your hands or forearms.
content.location: Back side of Warm-Up Boulder.

content.description: Start left of Burt Gives Blowjobs at the hole waist height, sit and moves right on flexing flakes to top out still shy of Burt Gives Blowjobs.   Fun moves, use it as a great warm-up for other problems in the woods.
content.location: Left arete Left of Burt Gives Blowjobs

content.description: This is a short but sweet run and jump problem. It literally has no holds, so you are forced to charge at the wall, place your foot on, and viciously jump to the sloping lip. Actually, it's easier in sneakers than climbing shoes. Difficult, friction-dependent, and frustrating but kind of fun if you like this sort of thing. It will feel v-impossible in the summer, guaranteed
content.protection: One pad will do, place it at the base of the start.
content.location: To the left of the obvious hand jam crack ''Valley Jams", this climbs the blank, vertical, face to the immediate left of it.

content.description: A dynamic, short problem up the face moving left.  Sit start as for Burt Gives Blowjobs, then move left hand up to the rail.  Cross with the right hand and match the rail, set up your feet, and dyno for the lip.  Topout on jugs.
content.protection: Pad, maybe a spotter if you're worried about hitting a tree.

content.description:
While this short arete may have once been a low quality V2, some holds broke and now it's an overlooked V4 with a V8ish variation.  Pull on to the arete using bad hands and feet and pop for the lip, then top it out.  Exiting left is the easier version. 

  The V8 variation uses the arete for the left hand and poor crimps on the wall right of the arete to start.  Dyno big with your right hand to a hidden jug and top it out.
content.location: Right face/arete of right warm-up boulder. Faces away from the trail.

content.description: Start standing with your right hand on a small sidepull crimp and left on the arete. Bump up the arete, hit a higher sidepull, and work out the slopey top. Heel hooks are your friend.
content.location: The arete left of The Extra Ion and right of the face with Pop on Top on it.

content.description:
A fun blunt arete.  Stand start with your left hand on the arete and right on an undercling, balance and deadpoint to a good crimp and head up to a slopey topout.  Good warm-up. 

  Watch out for the ledge rock if you fall.
content.location: Left line on right Warm-up Boulder.

content.description: Good Warm-up.   Start in the middle of the face and work up and a tiny bit to the right.   Fun Problem!   Top-out is a great time if you like flat top-outs, bring chalk if it is warm. There are no positive holds for the topout.
content.location: Central line on right Warm-up Boulder.

content.description: Right hand in rounded out seam, left hand around corner on shallow slope, thuggish left hand move to crystal nubs,and top out
content.location: Bulbous arete to the right of Damb the man

content.description:
Stand start with hands at head height in a good dish/jug. Get your feet on and pull up to gain good holds. Top out the problem. 

  Try to not use the tree for help up this thing.  

  This will be a good thing for beginner climbers to get on since it's only a few moves with big holds.
content.location: Just to the right of Forget Your Feet and to the left of the tree.

content.description: Stand start with good crystals at head height. Find your feet and pull up to another crystal. Bring your feet up higher and mantel the problem.
content.location: On the same boulder as Damn the Man right across from Valley Jams.

content.description:
This is a right-hand start to Burt's. Start sitting around the arete to the right with your right hand on a small sidepull and your left on the arete. Throw left hand up, and match right hand on the arete (crux). Move left until you can join Burt's for the topout.  

  This is a cool variation that adds a few more hard moves to a classic problem.
content.location: Warm Up Boulders

content.description: At first, I wasn't impressed, but this problem grew on me.  It has some tiny, bad holds, a crux deadpoint, and beat the hell out of my fingers.  Sit start the rear arete with some decent edges, pull up to a terrible sloper on the arete, then work your feet around and fight a savage barndoor as you deadpoint up to a very thin three-finger crimp.  Slap up to a good sidepull and finish up with a few easy moves to the top.
content.location: In the Warmup area, this is on the same boulder as Pop on Top and Scarred for Life.  Walk around back, away from the trail and find two low edges to start just left of the actual blunt arete.  Downclimb by the tree.

content.description: Sit start at the bottom of the very round and mossy arete. The crux is getting off the ground, unless the moss is wet and slippery.
content.location: Warm-up area, on the back of the boulder where Bert Gives... is.

content.description: The crux is getting off the ground. Sit Start with right hand on sharks tooth and left hand on and edge or side-pull just above it. Make a strenuous move to the jug that starts the regular problem. This move is made difficult by awkward feet and the slope of the hill you start on.
content.location: Warm-up boulder on left side of the boulder down and left of the perma-chalked jug that marks the start of the stand start route.

content.description: Start on the sharks tooth and the edge or side pull as you would for the sit start variation but instead of going to the jugs out right climb straight up to a slopey top out.
content.location: On the warmup boulder, start os for the "Doing Daddy Longlegs Sit Start" but climb straight up to a slopey top out.

content.description:
A classic problem that is also a great Warm-up. 

  Start crouching on the lowest jug in the middle of the face, then move up and right to the next jug before moving on to sloping ground with a hidden positive hold that helps the topout. Be mindful of where the footholds are, they disappear once you start to topout.
content.location: On warm-up boulder facing central hang-out area. Left line.

content.description: Sit Start as you would for Pop On Top and traverse left to the arete of Scared for Life. The key is staying low and using some interesting beta to get established on the arete, which is also the crux. The top out is slopey.
content.location: In the warm up boulders this is on the small boulder as Scared for Life. Starts for Pop on Top on the large ledges and move to a weird series of crimps then over to the arete as for Scared for Life.

content.description:
Stand start with your hands on a good sidepull. Find what feet you can and pull up to a good crystal above the lip. Move your feet around to find the best position for you. Pull hard and mantel the problem for the top out.  

  Have fun on this one it's got an interesting top out.
content.location: Left of Valley Jams on the far left arete.

content.description:
This problem may be short, but a lot of people can't get off the ground.  Sit start with two slopers on the lip, the left of which is crystally, and make a crux move to the big juggy pinch in the middle of the climb.  Finish straight up on crimps. 

  There used to be a little tree growing at the base of the climb which was not in the way.  Someone ripped it out.
content.location: Two problems to the right of Burt...  in the warmup area.

content.description: Sit start the arete with hands on each face and both feet on the left.  Move up with the right hand to a gaston and then up again to a sloper.  Work the feet up and mantel over the top (crux.)  There's a small, bad hold way up for the right hand to help with the mantel.
content.protection: Pads and spotters, kind of an akward landing to watch out for with the shalf boulder.
content.location: In the "warm up" area.  It's the obvious arete with the two foot shelf boulder at the base.

content.description: Sit start on the right side of the face with a crimpy, fingery flake and try not to roll down the hill.  Make a difficult pull up and left to the jug in the middle of Doing Daddy Long Legs and finish up that problem.
content.location: Right line on Warm-up Boulder.

content.description: Another hard Pawtuckaway one-mover that you may just want to just keep walking past. Start with an undercling for your left, and either a sidepull or an undercling for your right. Pick from the myriad of usable feet and pull on to the wall with difficulty, a long move/dyno or a bad intermediate gets you to the jug.
content.location: This is about ten feet left of "Burt Gives Blow Jobs"

content.description: Sit start and climb up and right following the jugs to the good top out. If you cant find a big hold you must have missed something. The crux is at the top but the holds are still very large.
content.location: In the Warm up boulders this is the juggy face to the right of Burt Gives Blowjobs. It starts sitting on the jugs move right following the jugs.

content.description: Start on an undercling and a decent left hand and climb up the rounded arete with small slopey crimps and good feet. The crux is getting off the ground, but by getting your but in the right position it is fairly easy.
content.location: The is on the boulder with Annie Oh. Located directly on the opposite side of the boulder as Annie Oh. Look for an undercling and some broken rock just to the right of this route.

content.description: These five boulders are where most people end up when they come to Blair Woods.  Problems of all styles abound, and while most of them are on the easy-moderate side, there are a few difficult classics thrown in for good measure.  Don't miss Burt Gives Blowjobs, Doing Daddy Longlegs, Scarred For Life, or Throwing Trumps.  Also worth noting is the fact that most of the topouts are sloping.
